prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText:
Our sensitivity is driven by the depth needed to detect the submm dust continuum in galaxies with PACS 100 micron detections. As outlined in the science case, we estimate 870 micron observed fluxes of >0.67mJy and so we request an RMS of 0.13 mJy in order to obtain SNR>5. The OT reports an integration time of ~2.5 minutes per source to reach this sensitivity (not including overheads and calibration).
In addition to individually detecting the continuum for each target, we will stack the spectral data (using available spectroscopic redshifts) to measure the average CO(5-4) in bins of galaxy density. There is a vast literature on the wide range for LIR/LCO and the excitation (spectral line energy distribution) for high redshift galaxies which may depend on if they are undergoing a starburst or forming stars at a more steady rate (e.g. Daddi et al. 2010; Genzel et al. 2010). If we conservatively assumed average values from these studies, we expect our targets with LIR>1.5e11Lsun to have CO(5-4) peak fluxes of >1.4mJy assuming a 300 km/s line width (typical for high redshift star forming galaxies, Carilli & Walter 2013). Given our continuum sensitivity of 0.13mJy over 7.5GHz, we will need to stack 5-10 galaxies to obtain a >5 sigma detection of the CO peak line flux. This will provide an independent measure of how the ISM varies with environment, as this line measures the average excited gas.

We focus this program in Band 7 as it is the most efficient for detecting the submm continuum in individual unresolved galaxies at z~0.7. Band 7 is also long enough wavelengths so that we are probing the Rayleigh-Jeans tail of the distribution where the dust is optically-thin enabling us to use our empirical ISM mass estimator. We note that wavelengths shorter than 250 micron rest-frame are not useful for this ISM mass estimator (see Scoville et al. 2014).
Given that the primary goal is a continuum measurement for each galaxy and since the CO lines are wide, the TDM correlator mode is optimal for our program. This will provide the full 7.5GHz bandwidth for the continuum measurement and a spectral resolution of 31.2 MHz adequate to sample the wide CO(5-4) line.
We have carefully placed the spectral windows so that they cover the CO(5-4) line for the redshifts of our targets in a single tuning. Specifically, the Science Goal 1 covers the redshift range z=0.720-0.741 and Science Goal 2 covers the redshift range z=0.741-0.760. Other spectral windows are placed to maximize the continuum sensitivity. The full continuum bandwidth is slightly less than 7.5GHz since we set a small overlap in the spectral windows where the CO lines are expected near the edges.
We note that the redshifts input into the OT were artificially fixed to one value of z=0.73 for all sources to overcome issues with the OT but we confirm that the CO (5-4) line for all targets in each science goal is well within the spectral windows we have defined.
Standard calibration, bandpass accuracy and data rate are sufficient for this program. We do not have any scheduling constraints or special technical considerations.

We are doing pointed observations of high redshift galaxies. Since we are interested in the integrated submm dust continuum for each galaxy, we request 2 arcsec spatial resolution - this resolution is sufficient to separate nearby sources but not so high that we will resolve our sources.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract:
We propose an experiment to test the role of environment in star formation; we will measure the ISM masses (and the average excited gas) for 101 high redshift star-forming galaxies along the cosmic web.
The large area of the COSMOS survey coupled with extensive redshifts has enabled mapping of the large scale structure. We focus our study at z~0.7 where the widest range of environments are seen, and near the beginning of the peak epoch of star formation. Using the galaxy density maps, we select spectroscopically-confirmed infrared galaxies across a range of environments (controlling for stellar mass and star formation rate).
We propose to measure the submillimeter continuum flux, which will be adopted as a surrogate for the ISM mass based on a well-tested, empirical relation. We will use these data to quantify how the ISM mass depends on the local galaxy density. In addition, we will stack the rest-frame spectral data in bins of galaxy density to measure the evolution in average excited gas immediately available for star formation.
This simple experiment will allow us to constrain the role that environment plays in star formation activity by moderating the ISM and excited gas.
prp:ObsProposal.prp:previousProposals: This is a resubmission of 2013.1.00107.S which was approved in Cycle 2 with C priority. As of the submission of this Cycle 3 proposal, no Cycle 2 observations were taken for this program. If some or all Cycle 2 observations are taken we will withdraw those targets from this Cycle 3 program.
